        <!-- Project Overview -->
        <div class="project-section">
            <h3>Project Overview</h3>
            <p>
                This project demonstrates a <strong>serverless automation</strong> for managing EC2 instances efficiently. The solution uses the AWS-provided 
                <strong>Instance Scheduler</strong> framework to automatically start and stop EC2 instances according to defined schedules stored in DynamoDB.
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Integrated <strong>GitHub</strong> and <strong>CircleCI</strong> for automated deployment (CI/CD).</li>
                <li>Deployed infrastructure via <strong>CloudFormation</strong> (Infrastructure as Code).</li>
                <li>Used <strong>EventBridge</strong> and <strong>Lambda</strong> for automated, time-based execution.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Architecture -->
        <div class="project-section alt-bg">
            <h3>Architecture Explanation</h3>
            <p>The architecture consists of fully managed AWS components working together:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>GitHub & CircleCI</strong> – Store source code and trigger automated deployments.</li>
                <li><strong>CloudFormation</strong> – Creates all AWS resources (Lambda, DynamoDB, EventBridge, IAM roles).</li>
                <li><strong>DynamoDB Table</strong> – Stores instance schedules (e.g., "office-hours").</li>
                <li><strong>EventBridge (Cron Job)</strong> – Runs every 5 minutes to trigger the Lambda function.</li>
                <li><strong>Lambda Function</strong> – Reads schedules and starts/stops EC2 instances based on current time.</li>
                <li><strong>EC2 Instances</strong> – Tagged with a schedule name that defines when they should run.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Key Learnings -->
        <div class="project-section">
            <h3>Key Learnings</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Deployed AWS Instance Scheduler using CloudFormation templates.</li>
                <li>Configured CircleCI environment variables securely for AWS deployment.</li>
                <li>Used serverless components (Lambda, DynamoDB, EventBridge) to build automation.</li>
                <li>Understood how tagging and scheduling reduce EC2 runtime costs.</li>
                <li>Learned how CI/CD integrates with Infrastructure as Code for real-world automation.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Best Practices -->
        <div class="project-section alt-bg">
            <h3>Notes & Best Practices</h3>
            <p>
                This project focused on automating EC2 lifecycle management for cost optimization. For production environments:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Use least-privilege IAM roles for Lambda and CloudFormation.</li>
                <li>Store AWS credentials securely using CircleCI environment variables or AWS Secrets Manager.</li>
                <li>Define granular schedules for different environments (dev, test, prod).</li>
                <li>Regularly review CloudWatch logs for Lambda function executions.</li>
            </ul>
